===Etymology 1===
First appeared around 1350–1400, either borrowed from {{etyl|dum|en}} {{term|clocke|lang=dum}} (Dutch {{term|klok||bell, clock|lang=nl}}), from {{proto|Germanic|lang=en}}; or from Northern {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|cloque||bell|lang=fro}} (French {{term|cloche|lang=fr}}), from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|clocca|lang=la}}.  Related to Old English {{term|clucge|lang=ang}}, German {{term|Glocke|lang=de}}, Swedish {{term|klocka|lang=sv}}, Irish {{term|clog|lang=ga}}, Breton {{term|kloc'h|lang=br}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# An [[instrument]] used to measure or keep track of [[time]]; a non-[[portable]] [[timepiece]].
# {{UK}} The [[odometer]] of a [[motor vehicle]].
#: ''This car has over 300,000 miles on the '''clock'''.''
# {{electronics}} An [[electrical signal]] that synchronizes [[timing]] among [[digital circuit|digital circuits]] of semiconductor chips or modules.

